Argv parsing and top-level dispatch for `ctx-context`; the only place `println!`-style output would otherwise creep in, so it's structured to render everything through an injected `Write` instead.

`Cli` (clap `Parser`) has an optional positional `path` and a `--hook` flag; `hook_mode()` exposes whether stdin must be read before `dispatch` is called (hook mode consumes stdin, path mode does not). `dispatch<E: Env, W: Write>(env: &E, base: &Path, cli: Cli, stdin: &str, out: &mut W) -> Result<(), CtxError>` is the sole entry point and branches on `cli.hook`:

- Hook mode calls `hook::run(env, base, stdin)`, which is fail-open by design — errors inside hook processing never propagate here; only an empty return value (meaning "nothing to inject") short-circuits to `Ok(())` without writing anything. A broken `out` writer is the only way this branch returns `Err`.
- Path mode requires `cli.path`, else returns `CtxError::Usage`. It checks `env.env_var(session::ENV_SESSION_ID)`: outside a session it calls `serve::chain_for` + `serve::render` directly; inside a session it calls `serve::fresh_chain_for` instead, which returns `Option<Vec<Node>>` — `None` means every node for that path was already shown this session, rendered as the fixed string `NOTHING_NEW`. This is the mechanism that keeps manual invocation and the `PostToolUse` hook sharing one dedup ledger (`crate::session`).

`out_err` wraps any writer `io::Error` as `CtxError::Io { path: "<stdout>", .. }` — the literal path string is a sentinel, not a real path. Changing `session::ENV_SESSION_ID` or `serve::fresh_chain_for`'s `Option` semantics requires updating both branches here in lockstep.